{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4102b550-207f-45b8-af17-e9cb3c3bc550","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n\n  <!-- Makes it installable via: dotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for …</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <RepositoryUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</RepositoryUrl>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n| Property | Why |\n|---|---|\n| `PackAsTool=true` | Tells `dotnet pack` to produce a tool package |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users will run (e.g. `my-mcp-server`) |\n| `OutputType=Exe` | Required — tools must be executables |\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push (get your API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # runs over stdio\n```\n\nThat's the minimum. No special MCP-specific packaging is needed — since it uses stdio transport, it just needs to be a runnable executable.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3584548d-b8ad-4f56-a62e-d892c5e07d94","outputTokens":546,"requestId":"C02A:2A497:1C6145A:1FF88BA:6A07C20B"},"id":"78471430-187e-4980-b667-2c7599fef5d3","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:02:13.890Z","parentId":"02d35e3c-699e-4847-a1